10
00:00:53,940 --> 00:00:59,420
And then you turn a corner into the financial district and time itself is running backwards.

11
00:00:59,960 --> 00:01:03,140
Cause and effect have basically swapped places.

12
00:01:04,080 --> 00:01:08,080
I mean, navigating a space like that wouldn't just be confusing.

13
00:01:08,300 --> 00:01:12,640
It would be fundamentally impossible.

14
00:01:12,640 --> 00:01:22,740
If the underlying logic of reality shifts every single time you cross a boundary, there's no shared baseline to make a decision.

15
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:27,940
You couldn't build a bridge, let alone, you know, a functioning society.

16
00:01:28,280 --> 00:01:38,620
And yet when you really step back and look at how we understand our world today, that is exactly the intellectual landscape we live in.

17
00:01:38,620 --> 00:01:42,540
We exist in this deeply, deeply fragmented reality.

18
00:01:42,720 --> 00:01:43,300
We really do.

19
00:01:43,400 --> 00:01:54,620
Because if you ask a physicist to explain the universe, they give you this system of, you know, cold, hard causality, deterministic equations, maybe some quantum probabilities.

20
00:01:55,500 --> 00:01:56,480
Yeah, it's all very mechanical.

21
00:01:56,820 --> 00:01:57,140
Right.

22
00:01:57,140 --> 00:02:06,280
But if you walk over to the economics department, they give you a world of rational actors, numerical value, transactional equilibrium.

23
00:02:07,140 --> 00:02:08,560
And then there's the philosophy department.

24
00:02:08,700 --> 00:02:09,160
Exactly.

25
00:02:09,520 --> 00:02:15,140
You sit alone in a quiet room and just examine your own subjective human experience.

26
00:02:15,140 --> 00:02:21,320
Like, the actual feeling of making a difficult choice or the sensation of time passing.

27
00:02:22,220 --> 00:02:27,380
And neither the physicist nor the economist can explain what is actually happening to you.

28
00:02:27,620 --> 00:02:28,140
Not at all.

29
00:02:28,200 --> 00:02:33,840
These frameworks all seem to operate by completely different, totally incompatible rules.

30
00:02:34,200 --> 00:02:36,920
It's a profound structural disconnect.

31
00:02:37,800 --> 00:02:41,860
Because physics has essentially, well, no room for human agency.

32
00:02:41,860 --> 00:02:50,920
Economics struggles to account for actual human meaning or qualitative well-being or, you know, ecological reality.

33
00:02:51,320 --> 00:02:51,380
Yeah.

34
00:02:51,900 --> 00:02:53,020
The stuff that actually matter.

35
00:02:53,140 --> 00:02:53,340
Right.

36
00:02:53,500 --> 00:03:05,380
And philosophy is just perpetually stuck in the middle, endlessly trying to figure out how your rich, internal, subjective experience of, like, listening to this conversation right now,

37
00:03:05,380 --> 00:03:13,040
how that could possibly arise from the blind mechanical interactions of atoms and molecules in your brain.

38
00:03:13,040 --> 00:03:16,320
Which brings us to our mission for this deep dive.

39
00:03:16,840 --> 00:03:23,880
Today, we are exploring this truly radical paper published in March, 2026 by an author named Fliction.

