See how the invention of money fundamentally distorts the geometry of those choices.

50
00:04:06,320 --> 00:04:07,140
And finally...

51
00:04:07,140 --> 00:04:08,320
The really dense part.

52
00:04:08,380 --> 00:04:08,700
Oh yeah.

53
00:04:08,820 --> 00:04:17,000
Finally, look at a highly technical mathematical blueprint the author proposes for saving complex systems from total collapse.

54
00:04:17,240 --> 00:04:20,460
And I think it's crucial to lay out the core thesis right up front.

55
00:04:20,460 --> 00:04:35,480
The author argues that the reason we have all these disconnected, incompatible maps of reality is that for centuries, our traditional frameworks have been looking at the universe entirely backward.

56
00:04:36,060 --> 00:04:36,980
Backward how?

57
00:04:36,980 --> 00:04:43,740
Well, in classical science, we've treated reality as being made up of static objects or static states.

58
00:04:44,020 --> 00:04:46,740
We think the universe is fundamentally made of things.

59
00:04:46,860 --> 00:04:49,660
You know, particles, planets, people, dollars.

60
00:04:50,020 --> 00:04:52,760
And then just occasionally those things change.

61
00:04:52,820 --> 00:04:58,800
So like a universe made of billiard balls just sitting on a table waiting for the cue ball to strike them.

62
00:04:59,440 --> 00:05:02,160
The being is the default and the doing is secondary.

63
00:05:02,160 --> 00:05:02,640
Exactly.

64
00:05:04,080 --> 00:05:04,340
Yeah.

65
00:05:05,240 --> 00:05:08,400
But this paper completely inverts that paradigm.

66
00:05:08,800 --> 00:05:21,460
It argues that transitions, like processes, choices, the irreversible changes from one state to another, those are the actual fundamental building blocks of reality.

67
00:05:21,620 --> 00:05:22,160
Wow.

68
00:05:22,360 --> 00:05:22,580
Yeah.

69
00:05:22,780 --> 00:05:26,860
Everything we think of as a static thing is actually just a secondary projection.

70
00:05:26,860 --> 00:05:32,420
It's a temporary shadow cast by an underlying continuous process.

71
00:05:33,240 --> 00:05:37,640
It's an ontology of becoming rather than an ontology of being.

72
00:05:37,700 --> 00:05:37,920
Okay.

73
00:05:38,020 --> 00:05:38,940
Let's unpack this.

74
00:05:39,020 --> 00:05:41,900
We have a massive intellectual journey ahead of us.

75
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:51,880
And before we really get into the mechanics, I just want to emphasize to you, the listener, that this paper touches on some incredibly heavy systemic topics.

76
00:05:51,960 --> 00:05:52,140
Yeah.

77
00:05:52,200 --> 00:05:53,080
It really goes there.

78
00:05:53,080 --> 00:05:59,760
It analyzes capitalism, the consolidation of corporate power, economic extraction, institutional decay.

79
00:06:00,180 --> 00:06:06,420
But our goal today is not to take any political sides or endorse any specific ideological viewpoint.

80
00:06:06,580 --> 00:06:07,380
Absolutely not.

81
00:06:07,380 --> 00:06:15,620
We are going to explore these concepts strictly as the formal, structural, and mathematical mechanics proposed by the author.

82
00:06:16,420 --> 00:06:21,740
We're treating this as an exploration of a deeply complex architectural model.

83
00:06:22,380 --> 00:06:31,440
Our job is simply to convey the fascinating structural arguments contained in the source material, regardless of where they point.

