00:06:31,440 --> 00:06:34,460
Because the math doesn't care about politics.

85
00:06:34,900 --> 00:06:36,340
It cares about structure.

86
00:06:37,220 --> 00:06:51,160
And if we want to understand how a structure as complex as a global finance or systemic power operates within this new process ontology, we actually have to start at the very bottom.

87
00:06:51,380 --> 00:06:52,260
The very bottom.

88
00:06:52,420 --> 00:06:52,560
Yeah.

89
00:06:52,580 --> 00:06:57,120
We have to start with one of the most famous intractable problems in all of science.

90
00:06:57,320 --> 00:06:59,580
You're talking about the hard problem of consciousness.

91
00:06:59,780 --> 00:07:00,540
The very one.

92
00:07:00,540 --> 00:07:10,840
So for anyone listening who might not, you know, spend their weekends reading cognitive science journals, the standard hard problem was famously formulated by the philosopher David Chalmers.

93
00:07:10,840 --> 00:07:20,440
It basically asks, how does physical matter create the rich, subjective, qualitative experience of being alive?

94
00:07:20,960 --> 00:07:24,260
Like, we can map the neural correlates of the brain.

95
00:07:24,960 --> 00:07:29,760
We can see exactly how the visual cortex processes the wavelength of red light.

96
00:07:30,540 --> 00:07:36,500
But none of that mechanical data explains what it actually feels like to see the color red.

97
00:07:36,600 --> 00:07:38,060
The actual experience.

98
00:07:38,160 --> 00:07:38,540
Yeah.

99
00:07:39,180 --> 00:07:47,680
How do blind, unfeeling neurons firing in the dark of your skull turn into the taste of coffee or the feeling of grief?

100
00:07:47,680 --> 00:07:57,860
And for decades, scientists and philosophers have just banged their heads against the wall, trying to solve this by looking for some missing mechanism in the brain.

101
00:07:58,320 --> 00:08:04,720
But Fliction's paper argues that the hard problem isn't actually about how matter makes mind at all.

102
00:08:04,780 --> 00:08:05,200
No?

103
00:08:05,360 --> 00:08:05,480
No.

104
00:08:05,480 --> 00:08:12,340
The paper proposes that the hard problem is entirely a categorical mismatch about time.

105
00:08:12,840 --> 00:08:13,700
A mismatch about time.

106
00:08:13,780 --> 00:08:13,940
Okay.

107
00:08:14,260 --> 00:08:17,420
That is a massive pivot from standard neuroscience.

108
00:08:17,980 --> 00:08:22,600
Let's break down what the paper means by that, starting with how physics views time.

109
00:08:22,760 --> 00:08:23,000
Sure.

110
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:30,500
If we look at fundamental physics, what the paper calls the third-person perspective, time is entirely symmetric.

111
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:36,300
In the mathematical models of general relativity, for example, time is just another coordinate.

112
00:08:36,460 --> 00:08:39,540
It's literally no different than up, down, left, or right.

113
00:08:39,660 --> 00:08:40,220
So spatial.

114
00:08:40,740 --> 00:08:41,260
Exactly.

115
00:08:41,540 --> 00:08:47,120
All moments, past, present, and future, they're equally real and equally accessible in the math.

116
00:08:47,120 --> 00:08:53,600
There is basically no mathematical variable in fundamental physics for the concept of now.

117
00:08:54,120 --> 00:09:03,760
So, to a physicist looking purely at the equations, the universe is just this giant frozen block of four-dimensional space-time.

118
00:09:03,920 --> 00:09:12,800
The Big Bang, the Roman Empire, you listening to this deep dive right now, and the eventual heat death of the universe,

119
00:09:12,800 --> 00:09:17,500
they all just exist statically within the geometry of the math.

120
00:09:17,620 --> 00:09:17,800
Yeah.

121
00:09:17,900 --> 00:09:19,780
It's often called the block universe theory.

122
00:09:20,580 --> 00:09:24,680
From that third-person objective view, nothing is technically happening.

123
00:09:24,780 --> 00:09:25,860
Everything simply is.

124
00:09:26,080 --> 00:09:26,360
Okay.

125
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:31,740
But your lived experience, the first-person perspective, is entirely different.

126
00:09:32,240 --> 00:09:35,440
The reality you and I inhabit is strictly asymmetric.

127
00:09:35,900 --> 00:09:38,700
The past is completely fixed and inaccessible.

128
00:09:38,700 --> 00:09:49,240
The future is completely open and unwritten, and you're trapped forever in this ever-moving, razor-thin sliver of experience called now.

129
00:09:49,860 --> 00:09:55,820
I was trying to visualize this profound disconnect when I was reading the paper, and here is how I think of it.

130
00:09:55,900 --> 00:09:58,980
Imagine you're watching a movie on a streaming service, right?

131
00:09:59,100 --> 00:09:59,680
Okay, yeah.

132
00:09:59,880 --> 00:10:07,100
The third-person perspective, the physics perspective, is the entire progress bar at the bottom of the screen.

133
00:10:07,100 --> 00:10:14,460
Every scene, from the opening credits to the finale, exists simultaneously on the server as data.

134
00:10:15,400 --> 00:10:20,480
To the server, there's no fundamental difference between minute 10 and minute 90.

135
00:10:20,660 --> 00:10:23,020
They're just spatial coordinates on a hard drive.

136
00:10:23,940 --> 00:10:28,060
That is a highly functional way to visualize the block universe.

137
00:10:28,260 --> 00:10:28,620
Thanks.

138
00:10:28,840 --> 00:10:30,100
And the first-person perspective.

139
00:10:30,100 --> 00:10:33,980
The first-person perspective is the actual playhead.

140
00:10:34,220 --> 00:10:39,340
It's the laser or the processing unit reading the data moment to moment.

141
00:10:39,860 --> 00:10:43,680
It only ever experiences one single frame at a time.

142
00:10:43,960 --> 00:10:46,960
It leaves a trail of watched frames behind it.

143
00:10:47,040 --> 00:10:48,200
That's the fixed past.

144
00:10:48,360 --> 00:10:51,780
And it looks toward an unplayed buffer, the open future.

145
00:10:52,200 --> 00:10:52,320
Right.

146
00:10:52,580 --> 00:10:57,540
The progress bar is symmetric, but the playhead's journey is aggressively asymmetric.

147
00:10:58,020 --> 00:10:59,540
It only moves in one direction.

148
00:10:59,540 --> 00:11:04,980
And this is exactly where the paper identifies the root of our fragmented reality.

149
00:11:06,340 --> 00:11:12,480
How has science historically dealt with this massive disconnect between the progress bar and the playhead?

150
00:11:12,560 --> 00:11:14,840
It usually sides with the progress bar, doesn't it?

151
00:11:15,160 --> 00:11:15,660
Exactly.

152
00:11:16,560 --> 00:11:26,440
Classical science usually treats the timeless symmetric progress, bar the objective math, as the ultimate fundamental truth of reality.

153
00:11:26,440 --> 00:11:30,120
And therefore, it treats your experience of the playhead.

154
00:11:30,120 --> 00:11:36,520
The feeling of time flowing, of making choices, of moving from the present into the future.

155
00:11:37,180 --> 00:11:42,660
It treats that as just a stubborn, persistent illusion created by human biology.

156
00:11:42,920 --> 00:11:46,280
It says that your feeling of now is just a trick of the brain.

157
00:11:46,280 --> 00:11:46,820
Right.

158
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:50,200
But this paper flips that completely upside down.

159
00:11:50,340 --> 00:11:52,600
It is a total ontological inversion.

160
00:11:53,400 --> 00:11:57,180
The paper argues that the first person lived experience of time flowing.

161
00:11:57,700 --> 00:12:05,320
That irreversible transition from potentiality into actuality is the primary foundational feature of reality.

162
00:12:05,400 --> 00:12:05,700
Wow.

163
00:12:05,700 --> 00:12:09,920
The symmetric progress bar of physics is just an abstraction.

164
00:12:10,280 --> 00:12:15,780
It's a model we build from our position at the playhead to try and understand the patterns of what we've already watched.

165
00:12:16,420 --> 00:12:18,020
The transition is real.

166
00:12:18,600 --> 00:12:20,480
The static block is the illusion.

167
00:12:20,480 --> 00:12:31,260
Okay, if we accept this premise, that the transition, the flow of time itself, is the fundamental building block of the universe, what is it made of?

168
00:12:31,660 --> 00:12:34,980
How does the paper define a transition mathematically?

169
00:12:35,660 --> 00:12:41,480
Because it breaks this down into three irreducible elements, which it calls the triad of reality.

170
00:12:42,320 --> 00:12:44,840
Causality, choice, and change.

171
00:12:44,840 --> 00:12:51,900
In a traditional deterministic worldview, you only really have causality.

172
00:12:52,820 --> 00:12:56,360
State A inevitably and mechanically leads to state B.

173
00:12:56,880 --> 00:13:06,920
But Fliction argues that mathematically, you cannot derive the actual lived flow of reality without all three of these elements interacting.

174
00:13:07,320 --> 00:13:09,220
Let's walk through the mechanics of the triad.

175
00:13:09,320 --> 00:13:10,600
First, we have causality.

176
00:13:11,040 --> 00:13:14,060
But it's not the old billiard ball causality, is it?

177
00:13:14,060 --> 00:13:14,280
No.

178
00:13:14,400 --> 00:13:18,160
In this framework, causality represents the third-person structure.

179
00:13:18,600 --> 00:13:21,020
It is the set of allowed future possibilities.

180
00:13:21,860 --> 00:13:27,700
Given the current state of the universe, the underlying laws dictate a menu of possible next states.

181
00:13:28,240 --> 00:13:30,200
Causality doesn't pick what happens next.

182
00:13:30,340 --> 00:13:34,620
It strictly defines the boundaries of what is mathematically allowed to happen next.

183
00:13:34,720 --> 00:13:35,640
It writes the menu.

184
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:37,500
Then comes the second element.

185
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:38,440
Choice.

186
00:13:38,440 --> 00:13:44,760
And I want to be very careful here, because we aren't just talking about human beings pondering what to eat for lunch.

187
00:13:45,760 --> 00:13:51,380
Choice, in this generalized ontological sense, is the first-person agency.

188
00:13:51,940 --> 00:13:59,780
It is the specific selection operator that picks one single path from that menu of causal possibilities.

189
00:13:59,780 --> 00:14:06,040
It is the mechanism that collapses the multiple potentials into a singular direction.

190
00:14:06,640 --> 00:14:08,100
And finally, change.

191
00:14:08,460 --> 00:14:13,140
Change is the irreversible actualization of that choice into history.

192
00:14:13,920 --> 00:14:24,460
It is the permanent act of taking that select impossibility and appending it to the record of the past, rendering it completely fixed and unalterable.

193
00:14:24,460 --> 00:14:30,200
Now, I have to push back here, because if you have a background in physics, your alarm bells are probably ringing right now.

194
00:14:30,200 --> 00:14:30,880
Oh, absolutely.

195
00:14:31,220 --> 00:14:38,800
If physics says the universe is governed by fundamental forces and quantum mechanics, where does choice actually live in the math?

196
00:14:39,320 --> 00:14:48,620
Are we suggesting that human free will or some cosmic consciousness is magically altering the trajectory of atoms in defiance of physics?

197
00:14:48,840 --> 00:14:50,660
It's a vital skepticism.

198
00:14:50,660 --> 00:14:55,000
The paper is absolutely not arguing for magic.

199
00:14:55,860 --> 00:15:01,380
This is where it introduces one of its most elegant mathematical concepts to bridge the gap.

200
00:15:01,900 --> 00:15:07,100
The dual aspect of indeterminacy, or what it calls the hard randomness symmetry.

201
00:15:07,960 --> 00:15:09,440
Let's dig into the math of this.

202
00:15:09,700 --> 00:15:15,380
How does the paper reconcile indeterminate quantum events with the concept of choice?

203
00:15:15,700 --> 00:15:18,640
Think about a highly unpredictable event.

204
00:15:18,640 --> 00:15:27,420
This could be a quantum superposition collapsing, or a highly complex non-linear event in a human neural network.

205
00:15:27,940 --> 00:15:33,360
There's a transition that cannot be perfectly predicted simply by looking at the past states.

206
00:15:33,560 --> 00:15:38,240
An indeterminate transition, we don't know exactly what will happen until it happens.

207
00:15:38,420 --> 00:15:38,700
Right.

208
00:15:39,100 --> 00:15:40,980
Now, how do we describe that event?

209
00:15:40,980 --> 00:15:53,600
The paper proves mathematically that an external third-person observer, someone looking at this system from the outside, can only describe this unpredictable event using a probability distribution.

210
00:15:53,800 --> 00:15:55,400
Because they can't see the whole picture.

211
00:15:55,920 --> 00:15:56,360
Exactly.

212
00:15:56,760 --> 00:16:01,220
To the outside observer, it looks like randomness or stochastic noise.

213
00:16:01,220 --> 00:16:06,420
They lack the internal contextual information, so they just see a dice roll.

214
00:16:06,980 --> 00:16:12,720
They see a 70% chance of outcome A and a 30% chance of outcome B.

215
00:16:12,900 --> 00:16:14,720
Because they are looking at the menu.

216
00:16:14,880 --> 00:16:16,560
They are studying the causality.

217
00:16:16,560 --> 00:16:17,280
Yes.

218
00:16:17,920 --> 00:16:33,200
But, and this is the theoretical breakthrough, a first-person observer looking from the inside of that exact same system, experiencing that exact same indeterminate transition, experiences it as choice.

219
00:16:33,380 --> 00:16:33,940
Whoa.

220
00:16:34,480 --> 00:16:39,620
Randomness and choice are not two different phenomena fighting for control of the universe.

221
00:16:40,020 --> 00:16:44,260
They are two different informational descriptions of the exact same event.

222
00:16:44,260 --> 00:16:48,780
I want to make sure the listener really grasps this, because it's mind-bending.

223
00:16:49,280 --> 00:16:55,820
The paper uses category theory to formalize this, specifically pointing to adjoint functors.

224
00:16:56,380 --> 00:17:03,600
Now, in mathematics, a functor is basically a mapping that translates the structure of one mathematical category into another.

225
00:17:03,740 --> 00:17:04,220
Precisely.

226
00:17:04,340 --> 00:17:09,460
It preserves the relationships between objects when you move them to a new context.

227
00:17:09,460 --> 00:17:28,660
So, if I understand the paper's proof, it's saying that when you apply a forgetful functor, meaning you strip away the internal, subjective, first-person context of an event to look at it objectively, the math literally collapses into pure probability.

228
00:17:28,860 --> 00:17:29,460
It becomes randomness.

229
00:17:29,460 --> 00:17:30,280
randomness.

230
00:17:30,420 --> 00:17:30,700
Yes.

231
00:17:30,700 --> 00:17:44,000
But when you apply the free functor, adding the internal lived context back into the equation, that exact same mathematical event resolves into the geometry of choice.

232
00:17:44,180 --> 00:17:46,300
It's the exact mechanism.

233
00:17:46,520 --> 00:17:47,720
They're dual aspects.

234
00:17:47,720 --> 00:17:56,060
Like, if I'm watching you deliberate over a difficult career decision, I cannot possibly compute the entirety of your internal state.

235
00:17:56,520 --> 00:18:01,260
To me, from the outside, you have a probabilistic chance of quitting your job or staying.

236
00:18:01,460 --> 00:18:03,300
It looks like a stochastic equation.

237
00:18:03,400 --> 00:18:03,760
Sure.

238
00:18:03,940 --> 00:18:06,580
But inside your mind, you aren't rolling a die.

239
00:18:06,840 --> 00:18:11,960
You are weighing the options, feeling the friction of the decision, and actively selecting a path.

240
00:18:11,960 --> 00:18:19,860
So, the randomness I see is just the shadow cast by your internal choice, simply because I don't have access to your first-person perspective.

241
00:18:20,400 --> 00:18:20,760
Yes.

242
00:18:21,620 --> 00:18:27,420
And this brings us to the paper's ultimate, staggering conclusion about the hard problem.

243
00:18:28,200 --> 00:18:34,780
Consciousness is not some magical substance or emergent smoke generated by complex brain matter.

244
00:18:35,760 --> 00:18:39,940
Consciousness is the internal experience of temporal asymmetry.

245
00:18:39,940 --> 00:18:48,500
It is simply what it feels like from the inside to resolve multiple possibilities into a single irreversible history.

246
00:18:49,140 --> 00:18:54,620
If you are the playhead moving across the data, consciousness is the friction of that movement.

247
00:18:54,820 --> 00:18:55,160
Exactly.

248
00:18:55,440 --> 00:19:01,420
It's the sensation of the transition itself that completely reshapes how we view our place in the universe.

249
00:19:01,820 --> 00:19:03,880
We aren't objects that have consciousness.

250
00:19:04,360 --> 00:19:07,360
We are the active process of time flowing.

251
00:19:07,360 --> 00:19:09,580
It shifts the foundation entirely.

252
00:19:10,480 --> 00:19:13,180
Reality isn't a static collection of objects.

253
00:19:13,600 --> 00:19:18,200
It is an endless sequence of choices resolving into irreversible history.

254
00:19:18,500 --> 00:19:20,760
But that creates a massive new problem.

255
00:19:21,180 --> 00:19:26,200
If reality is just this endless sequence of choices, who or what is actually making them?

256
00:19:26,800 --> 00:19:34,500
In a framework where objects don't fundamentally exist, we have to completely throw out our traditional definition of what a person is.

257
00:19:34,500 --> 00:19:35,060
We do.

258
00:19:35,060 --> 00:19:41,520
Which brings us to the paper's second major phase, redefining the self and the geometry of possibility.

259
00:19:42,100 --> 00:19:48,540
If we accept the premise that processes are fundamental, you cannot define yourself by your physical body.

260
00:19:48,860 --> 00:19:51,000
I mean, your cells replace themselves constantly.

261
00:19:51,440 --> 00:19:53,580
Your physical state is always in flux.

262
00:19:53,880 --> 00:19:53,960
Right.

263
00:19:54,280 --> 00:20:00,680
You also cannot define yourself as a static, unchanging soul floating somewhere outside of time.

264
00:20:00,680 --> 00:20:03,840
So how does flexion define the human identity?

265
00:20:04,240 --> 00:20:10,720
Because the paper introduces this formal mathematical definition of the self, represented as an ordered pair.

266
00:20:11,740 --> 00:20:17,280
The equation is S sub T equals H sub T omega sub T.

267
00:20:18,060 --> 00:20:20,540
Let's translate this into English for the listener.

268
00:20:20,740 --> 00:20:24,100
The first variable, H sub T, is your history.

269
00:20:24,700 --> 00:20:28,360
And the second variable, omega sub T, is your horizon.

270
00:20:28,360 --> 00:20:29,860
History and horizon.

271
00:20:30,120 --> 00:20:31,100
Let's start with history.

272
00:20:31,420 --> 00:20:32,240
H sub T.

273
00:20:32,240 --> 00:20:38,580
Your history is the irreversible, append-only record of every event, every choice, and every

274
00:20:38,580 --> 00:20:41,740
transition that has ever happened to you or been made by you.

275
00:20:42,080 --> 00:20:47,020
It is the absolute sum of your past, recorded in strict chronological order.

276
00:20:47,840 --> 00:20:53,580
Crucially, in this math, history can never be erased, altered, or uncollapsed.

277
00:20:54,020 --> 00:20:55,400
It is permanently fixed.

278
00:20:55,400 --> 00:21:00,920
Okay, and based on that fixed history, we get the second variable, omega sub T, the horizon.

279
00:21:01,560 --> 00:21:06,740
The horizon is your constrained space of possible futures.

280
00:21:07,380 --> 00:21:13,500
It is the specific, mathematically defined set of possibilities that are open to you right

281
00:21:13,500 --> 00:21:18,880
now in this exact moment, based entirely on what has happened in your history.

282
00:21:18,880 --> 00:21:26,000
To help visualize this, let's think about how an RPG video game works, with those complex

283
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:29,400
skill trees, or like a massive branching narrative.

284
00:21:29,840 --> 00:21:34,580
Let's use the concept of a high-dimensional manifold, or a phase space.

285
00:21:35,120 --> 00:21:41,140
Imagine your life is a point moving through this massive, multidimensional web of paths.

286
00:21:41,140 --> 00:21:49,280
Your history, your H sub T, is the exact unchangeable red line you've drawn through that web from the

287
00:21:49,280 --> 00:21:51,520
moment you were born up until today.

288
00:21:51,880 --> 00:21:57,300
And because you walk down that specific red line, you are standing at a very specific intersection

289
00:21:57,300 --> 00:21:57,740
right now.

290
00:21:57,800 --> 00:21:57,980
Right.

291
00:21:58,280 --> 00:22:04,340
And your horizon, omega sub T, consists of the specific streets branching out in front of you

292
00:22:04,340 --> 00:22:06,300
from this exact intersection.

293
00:22:06,300 --> 00:22:12,900
Like, if you spent your history studying medicine, the become a surgeon path is open and illuminated

294
00:22:12,900 --> 00:22:13,840
in your horizon.

295
00:22:14,240 --> 00:22:19,880
If I didn't study medicine, that path physically does not exist in my omega sub T.

296
00:22:20,280 --> 00:22:22,760
It is completely inaccessible to me.

297
00:22:23,260 --> 00:22:27,740
So the paper is arguing that myself is not my body or my thoughts.

298
00:22:28,200 --> 00:22:34,320
Myself is literally just the combination of the specific path I've walked and the specific

299
00:22:34,320 --> 00:22:37,600
set of roads I am now mathematically allowed to choose from.

300
00:22:38,100 --> 00:22:42,020
That is the structural reality of identity in this framework.

301
00:22:42,660 --> 00:22:45,600
But the paper takes it a massive step further.

302
00:22:46,160 --> 00:22:50,140
It's not just that your history dictates which options are available.

303
00:22:50,140 --> 00:22:56,080
Your history actively dictates how you feel about those options and how likely you are

304
00:22:56,080 --> 00:22:56,680
to take them.

305
00:22:57,620 --> 00:23:03,300
This is where the author introduces preference fields, denoted mathematically as psi sub T.

306
00:23:03,300 --> 00:23:04,540
Perference fields.

307
00:23:05,060 --> 00:23:08,940
This sounds like we're applying the physics of gravity to human desires.

308
00:23:09,280 --> 00:23:11,380
That is essentially what the math is doing.

309
00:23:11,880 --> 00:23:18,260
The paper models this using what calls RSVP field dynamics, which stands for scalar density,

310
00:23:18,880 --> 00:23:20,820
vector flow, and entropy fields.

311
00:23:21,100 --> 00:23:22,980
Let's ground that math for the listener.

312
00:23:23,140 --> 00:23:28,660
If I am standing at my intersection of choices, how does an RSVP field actually work on me?

313
00:23:28,660 --> 00:23:35,740
Imagine your horizon of possibilities isn't a flat map, but a physical, topological landscape.

314
00:23:36,400 --> 00:23:37,760
It has hills and valleys.

315
00:23:38,280 --> 00:23:43,360
When you make a choice to walk down a certain path, you don't just move to a new location.

316
00:23:43,900 --> 00:23:46,400
Your action physically deforms the landscape.

317
00:23:47,560 --> 00:23:51,200
The scalar density represents the accumulation of your past choices.

318
00:23:51,860 --> 00:23:57,300
The more you choose a certain type of response, the more mass that choice accumulates.

319
00:23:57,300 --> 00:24:00,260
And in physics, mass creates gravity.

320
00:24:00,780 --> 00:24:02,560
It bends the space around it.

321
00:24:02,740 --> 00:24:03,120
Exactly.

322
00:24:03,380 --> 00:24:08,640
Or, to use a more terrestrial analogy, imagine walking through a really dense forest.

323
00:24:09,880 --> 00:24:13,920
The first time you bushwhack a path, it is incredibly difficult.

324
00:24:14,120 --> 00:24:18,640
There is high friction, but the mere act of walking it presses down the grass and breaks

325
00:24:18,640 --> 00:24:19,220
the branches.

326
00:24:19,780 --> 00:24:25,920
The next time you face a similar choice, that path represents a vector flow of lesser resistance.

327
00:24:25,920 --> 00:24:31,500
The dirt path is physically easier to walk down than hacking through the jungle again?

328
00:24:31,860 --> 00:24:32,200
Yes.

329
00:24:32,920 --> 00:24:38,580
Your prior choices create a gravitational pull towards similar choices in the future.

330
00:24:39,280 --> 00:24:42,800
The field of your possibilities has been topologically deformed.

331
00:24:43,480 --> 00:24:50,080
The entropy variable in the RSVP dynamics measures how much your horizon is narrowing or broadening

332
00:24:50,080 --> 00:24:51,640
based on those grooves.

333
00:24:52,180 --> 00:24:56,780
So, your preferences aren't just abstract, floating ideas in your mind.

334
00:24:57,220 --> 00:25:00,940
They are structural modifications to the geometry of your future.

335
00:25:01,040 --> 00:25:05,180
This has profound implications for how we think about human behavior.

336
00:25:05,560 --> 00:25:12,380
If I choose to react to a stressful situation at work with, say, intense anger today, I'm not

337
00:25:12,380 --> 00:25:13,940
just having an emotional moment.

338
00:25:13,940 --> 00:25:18,460
Mathematically, I am digging a trench in my possibility space.

339
00:25:18,480 --> 00:25:18,720
Exactly.

340
00:25:19,140 --> 00:25:25,200
Tomorrow, when I face another stressor, the anger path is physically wider and steeper in

341
00:25:25,200 --> 00:25:26,620
my mathematical horizon.

342
00:25:26,980 --> 00:25:29,160
The vector flow is pushing me that way.

343
00:25:29,520 --> 00:25:31,360
I am more likely to fall down it.

344
00:25:31,820 --> 00:25:37,900
It's a formal geometric explanation for habits, neuroplasticity, and even addiction.

345
00:25:37,900 --> 00:25:44,300
It completely bridges the gap between the psychology of habit and the mathematics of probability.

346
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:49,340
Yourself is a dynamic, constantly evolving geometry of choices.

347
00:25:49,700 --> 00:25:57,360
So, I am my fixed history, my specific menu of future options, and the gravitational trenches

348
00:25:57,360 --> 00:25:58,620
I've dug in that menu.

349
00:25:59,340 --> 00:26:04,640
I exist as a geometric shape in a space of possibilities.

350
00:26:04,640 --> 00:26:08,500
But this raises the ultimate problem of human existence.

351
00:26:09,240 --> 00:26:09,500
What's that?

352
00:26:09,860 --> 00:26:13,660
That mathematical model works perfectly for me sitting alone in a room.

353
00:26:13,820 --> 00:26:13,960
Yeah.

354
00:26:14,040 --> 00:26:17,580
But what happens when I walk out my front door and need to interact with you?

355
00:26:18,060 --> 00:26:23,240
You have your own history, your own complex branching roads, and your own deep trenches.

356
00:26:23,780 --> 00:26:28,500
We have completely different, totally subjective possibility spaces.

357
00:26:28,900 --> 00:26:31,380
How on earth do we ever coordinate?

358
00:26:31,720 --> 00:26:34,080
And this right here is the hinge of the entire paper.

359
00:26:34,080 --> 00:26:40,360
This exact question, the collision of subjective possibility spaces, is how the author brilliantly

360
00:26:40,360 --> 00:26:47,780
transitions from the quantum physics of consciousness directly into the brutal realities of macroeconomics.

361
00:26:47,980 --> 00:26:50,440
Because to coordinate, we have to interact.

362
00:26:50,800 --> 00:26:50,940
Yeah.

363
00:26:50,960 --> 00:26:55,940
And when my geometry collides with your geometry, things get incredibly complicated.

364
00:26:55,940 --> 00:27:02,220
When multiple agents with different possibility spaces need to interact, they merge to create

365
00:27:02,220 --> 00:27:05,820
what the paper calls an aggregate possibility structure.

366
00:27:06,320 --> 00:27:14,580
It is a massive, incredibly complex, high-dimensional web of overlapping histories, desires, physical

367
00:27:14,580 --> 00:27:16,580
limitations, and potential futures.

368
00:27:16,580 --> 00:27:24,820
If my life is a 3D landscape of paths, society is billions of those landscapes stacked on top

369
00:27:24,820 --> 00:27:27,900
of each other, intercepting in impossible ways.

370
00:27:27,960 --> 00:27:28,220
Yes.

371
00:27:28,680 --> 00:27:35,040
And navigating that high-dimensional aggregate structure is cognitively impossible for human

372
00:27:35,040 --> 00:27:35,400
beings.

373
00:27:35,760 --> 00:27:36,000
Right.

374
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:38,220
We just do not have the computational power.

375
00:27:38,360 --> 00:27:38,640
Right.

376
00:27:38,640 --> 00:27:43,420
If you want to trade a loaf of bread for a pair of shoes, you cannot compute the deep historical

377
00:27:43,420 --> 00:27:49,240
resonance, the ecological impact, the labor history, and the future implications of that

378
00:27:49,240 --> 00:27:51,280
interaction for both you and the shoemaker.

379
00:27:51,540 --> 00:27:54,220
The information density is just way too high.

380
00:27:54,640 --> 00:27:57,700
The friction of the playhead would grind to a halt.

381
00:27:58,060 --> 00:28:00,900
We would be paralyzed by the complexity of the math.

382
00:28:00,900 --> 00:28:07,520
So human beings invent a tool to do the computing for us, to compress the aggregate possibility

383
00:28:07,520 --> 00:28:10,120
space into something we can quickly navigate.

384
00:28:10,420 --> 00:28:11,780
We invent money.

385
00:28:12,220 --> 00:28:16,700
And I have to say, of all the theories of money I've read in economics, money as a store of

386
00:28:16,700 --> 00:28:22,560
value, money as a medium of exchange, money as a ledger of debt, this paper's mathematical

387
00:28:22,560 --> 00:28:25,440
definition is by far the most fascinating.

388
00:28:25,440 --> 00:28:32,760
It redefines money not as a physical object or even a social belief, but as a mathematical

389
00:28:32,760 --> 00:28:33,580
function.

390
00:28:34,020 --> 00:28:39,800
It defines money formally as a projection functor, denoted as M sub T.

391
00:28:40,420 --> 00:28:43,240
We talked about functors earlier when discussing consciousness.

392
00:28:43,800 --> 00:28:47,600
A functor maps one complex category of math onto another.

393
00:28:47,880 --> 00:28:49,780
So how does the money functor work?

394
00:28:49,880 --> 00:28:55,420
The money functor takes this unbelievably complex, multidimensional web of human beings.

395
00:28:55,440 --> 00:29:01,240
Human possibilities, relationships, ecological realities, and historical context.

396
00:29:01,600 --> 00:29:05,920
And it projects all of it down into a single one-dimensional scalar number.

397
00:29:06,600 --> 00:29:07,180
A price.

398
00:29:07,760 --> 00:29:08,820
A monetary value.

399
00:29:09,060 --> 00:29:14,900
It takes the giant, tangled, high-dimensional knot of human society and flattens it into a

400
00:29:14,900 --> 00:29:15,720
single line.

401
00:29:16,180 --> 00:29:17,500
A number on a spreadsheet.

402
00:29:18,080 --> 00:29:22,380
It collapses the structural complexities so that we can coordinate quickly.

403
00:29:22,380 --> 00:29:30,260
It answers the incredibly difficult question of, how much of my possibility space do I need

404
00:29:30,260 --> 00:29:36,460
to sacrifice to access this specific part of your possibility space with a simple integer?

405
00:29:37,540 --> 00:29:42,460
It is a brilliant, necessary tool for scaling human cooperation.

406
00:29:42,460 --> 00:29:46,720
But, and this is the crux of the paper's transition into economics.

407
00:29:47,480 --> 00:29:49,740
The paper isn't just describing what money does.

408
00:29:49,840 --> 00:29:54,660
It is issuing a massive, mathematically rigorous warning about how it does it.

409
00:29:55,040 --> 00:30:01,120
The author mathematically proved that this monetary projection functor is non-injective and non-isometric.

410
00:30:01,300 --> 00:30:03,180
Those are critical mathematical properties.

411
00:30:03,480 --> 00:30:08,280
We really need to unpack what happens when a projection is non-injective and non-isometric.

412
00:30:08,280 --> 00:30:10,720
Let's start with non-injective.

413
00:30:11,180 --> 00:30:15,800
I'll use an analogy for the listener to visualize what this means for data compression.

414
00:30:16,380 --> 00:30:20,720
Imagine you have an incredibly high-resolution 3D movie file.

415
00:30:21,160 --> 00:30:28,400
It has surround sound, 4K visuals, multiple language tracks, director's commentary, deep emotional

416
00:30:28,400 --> 00:30:28,860
resonance.

417
00:30:29,320 --> 00:30:30,800
It's a 100 gigabyte file.

418
00:30:31,100 --> 00:30:37,300
That represents human reality, the full, rich, aggregate possibility structure.

419
00:30:37,300 --> 00:30:44,960
Now imagine compressing that entire 100 gigabyte movie into a tiny, silent, heavily pixelated

420
00:30:44,960 --> 00:30:46,340
2 megabyte GIF.

421
00:30:46,640 --> 00:30:51,320
You are projecting from a high-dimensional space down to a low-dimensional space.

422
00:30:51,500 --> 00:30:51,780
Exactly.

423
00:30:51,940 --> 00:30:56,420
Now you can technically email that GIF across the world in a fraction of a second.

424
00:30:56,840 --> 00:30:59,640
It is highly efficient for communication and coordination.

425
00:31:00,200 --> 00:31:03,140
But the compression is profoundly lossy.

426
00:31:03,140 --> 00:31:08,800
You have permanently lost the depth, the audio, the pacing, and the structural richness of

427
00:31:08,800 --> 00:31:09,700
the original file.

428
00:31:10,080 --> 00:31:13,720
And that loss is exactly what non-injective means in topology.

429
00:31:14,140 --> 00:31:19,500
It means that multiple, entirely different complex inputs in the 3D space will be squashed

430
00:31:19,500 --> 00:31:24,000
down and map onto the exact same simplified output in the 2D space.

431
00:31:24,380 --> 00:31:27,380
The nuance is mathematically destroyed in the translation.

432
00:31:27,380 --> 00:31:28,020
Right.

433
00:31:28,020 --> 00:31:34,740
And non-isometric means that the actual distances, the relative importance and relationships of

434
00:31:34,740 --> 00:31:42,300
things in the 3D space, are completely warped and distorted when you flatten them onto a 1D line.

435
00:31:42,980 --> 00:31:48,320
Things that were far apart might look close together, and things that were connected might be severed.

436
00:31:48,320 --> 00:31:52,760
What is terrifying here is the sociological implication of this math.

437
00:31:53,800 --> 00:31:57,880
The paper called this consequence compression-induced equivalence.

438
00:31:58,680 --> 00:32:04,220
Because the monetary metric squashes all these rich dimensions into a single scalar number,

439
00:32:05,020 --> 00:32:09,880
two completely different human actions, with vastly different impacts on our actual lived

440
00:32:09,880 --> 00:32:13,720
reality, can end up having the exact same monetary value.

441
00:32:13,720 --> 00:32:18,600
Let's give the listener a concrete example of compression-induced equivalence in the real

442
00:32:18,600 --> 00:32:18,960
world.

443
00:32:19,420 --> 00:32:22,120
Let's think about the economy of a mid-sized town.

444
00:32:22,420 --> 00:32:23,880
Okay, let's look at Action A.

445
00:32:24,400 --> 00:32:28,140
A group of citizens starts a local cooperative grocery store.

446
00:32:28,780 --> 00:32:32,080
They source food from local farmers, paying them fairly.

447
00:32:32,560 --> 00:32:34,720
They provide healthy food to a food desert.

448
00:32:35,180 --> 00:32:39,660
They train employees, creating deep social bonds and community resilience.

449
00:32:39,660 --> 00:32:43,880
The structural richness of the town skyrockets.

450
00:32:44,680 --> 00:32:50,180
The possibility spaces, the omega subs of everyone involved, expand beautifully.

451
00:32:50,780 --> 00:32:57,140
But let's say the net monetary profit generated at the end of the year is, hypothetically, $100,000.

452
00:32:57,780 --> 00:33:02,960
A highly complex, structurally rich process that outputs a scalar value of $100,000.

453
00:33:03,280 --> 00:33:04,820
Now look at Action B.

454
00:33:04,820 --> 00:33:10,900
A massive private equity firm buys up the only affordable housing complex in that exact same

455
00:33:10,900 --> 00:33:11,240
town.

456
00:33:11,600 --> 00:33:16,500
They evict half the tenants, double the rent for the rest, refuse to do maintenance, and

457
00:33:16,500 --> 00:33:18,140
extract every possible cent.

458
00:33:18,740 --> 00:33:20,460
This stress destroys families.

459
00:33:21,120 --> 00:33:23,480
The community fabric is completely torn apart.

460
00:33:23,960 --> 00:33:26,920
The structural richness of the town is severely degraded.

461
00:33:27,340 --> 00:33:30,500
The possibility spaces of those renters physically shrink.

462
00:33:30,500 --> 00:33:35,940
But the net monetary profit generated for the firm is also exactly $100,000.

463
00:33:36,980 --> 00:33:37,240
Wow.

464
00:33:37,560 --> 00:33:45,420
So, to the metric, to the projection functor of money, Action A and Action B are perfectly

465
00:33:45,420 --> 00:33:46,920
mathematically equivalent.

466
00:33:47,580 --> 00:33:52,980
The system is fundamentally blind to the difference between building a community and cannibalizing

467
00:33:52,980 --> 00:33:53,220
it.

468
00:33:53,380 --> 00:33:53,940
Precisely.

469
00:33:53,940 --> 00:34:01,500
Because the metric only perceives the 1D scalar number, it cannot see the 3D structural destruction.

